"<h3>Art and State</h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p><span class=\"image-wrapper inline-image\"><img alt=\"Hyacinthe Rigaud, Louis XIV, 1701. Oil on canvas, 9’2” x 6’3”. Musée du Louvre, Paris\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/d0dfb0faa9843a0f0973f98e12e3294bbc83b27d.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">Hyacinthe Rigaud, <em>Louis XIV</em>, 1701, oil on canvas, 9&rsquo;2&rdquo; x 6&rsquo;3&rdquo;. Mus&eacute;e du Louvre, Paris</span></span>The early seventeenth century was marked by unrest and near constant warfare; however, by the mid seventeenth century, France had emerged as Europe&rsquo;s largest and most powerful country. France, under Louis XIV, was an absolute monarchy where full power resided with the king. As an absolute monarch, Louis was not subject to any constitutional limitations, leading him to declare &ldquo;l&rsquo;etat, c&rsquo;est moi&rdquo; (&ldquo;I am the state&rdquo;). Louis ruled by divine right, receiving his authority directly from God. The concept of divine right allowed Louis to quash emerging rebellions while establishing legitimacy. Louis became known as <em>le Roi Soleil</em>, the Sun King, furthering his claim of divine lineage by recalling the ancient Greek god Apollo and declaring himself, in his usual modest manner, to be the center of the universe.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Recognizing the importance of propaganda, Louis and his advisors embarked on many large-scale projects, most memorably the expansion of Versailles from a rather unassuming (by royal standards, at least) hunting lodge to an enormous, gilded (and mirrored) palace. Versailles reinforced the image of the Sun King and infused the Baroque style with classical elements, visually linking Louis&rsquo; rule to the might of Imperial Rome. As the leading patron of the era, Louis XIV employed a workshop of artists and architects; Hyacinthe Rigaud became the principal painter to the king. &nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><span class=\"block-image image-wrapper\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/683ce13b0b50525b48cf2c87e58a688275fc04e6.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">Left: Hyacinthe Rigaud, <em>Louis XIV</em>, 1701, oil on canvas, 9&rsquo;2&rdquo; x 6&rsquo;3&rdquo;&nbsp;(Mus&eacute;e du Louvre), Paris; right: Anthony van Dyck, <em>Charles I at the Hunt</em>, c. 1635, oil on canvas, 2.66 x 2.07 m (Mus&eacute;e du Louvre)</span></span></p>\n"
"\n"
"<h3>&ldquo;L&rsquo;etat, c&rsquo;est moi&rdquo;</h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p><span class=\"image-wrapper inline-image\"><img alt=\"Face (detail), Hyacinthe Rigaud, Louis XIV, 1701. Oil on canvas, 9’2” x 6’3”. Musée du Louvre, Paris\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/22f49c07ffd4c41402c8bbfe5570664386bad328.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">Face (detail), Hyacinthe Rigaud, <em>Louis XIV</em>, 1701, oil on canvas, 9&rsquo;2&rdquo; x 6&rsquo;3&rdquo; (Mus&eacute;e du Louvre, Paris)</span></span>Rigaud&rsquo;s monumental portrait displays a life-size, full-body depiction of Louis XIV. The composition recalls Anthony Van Dyck&rsquo;s 1635 <em>Charles I Dismounted.&nbsp;</em>Louis, as the focal point, stands in the center of the canvas, his body angled slightly while his face is turned to meet the viewer with the confidence and directness expected from a king.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Billowing embroidered silk curtains form an honorific canopy over the King&rsquo;s head while the lavish carpeting creates an opulent environment worthy of the king&rsquo;s presence. To the left, a marble column sits atop a gilded base, symbolizing the strength of the monarch while again recalling the classical era.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
