"<span class=\"image-wrapper inline-image\"><img alt=\"Girl's caribou skin parka, Inuit, early 19th century C.E., 76 cm high, from West Greenland © Trustees of the British Museum. This parka has contrasting mosaic-work made of the white belly skin of a young caribou. The curved flaps, front and rear, are characteristic of Arctic women's clothing. The edge of the hood would have been finished with a ruff or fringe of fur from animals such as wolf or wolverine. Their glossy hairs allow the accumulated ice, from breath and snow fall, to be shaken away.\n"
