"\n"
"<p><span>Although the Andrews purchased their conversation portrait from Gainsborough, something is missing from the work. Bare canvas surrounds Mrs. Andrews&#39; hands, folded in her lap. No one knows exactly what Gainsborough intended to paint in that space, if he intended to paint anything at all. Some scholars have suggested that Mrs. Andrews was meant to hold a dead game bird, the result of a successful hunting trip by her husband. Such an inclusion would emphasize the couple&rsquo;s control over their land, but a bloody animal would ruin Mrs. Andrews&rsquo; elaborate dress, and therefore seems unlikely.&nbsp;</span></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Another possibility for Mrs. Andrews&rsquo; lap is that the blank space was intended for a baby. Regardless of what was meant to go in that spot, Gainsborough never added it in. Modern scholars consider the painting to be &ldquo;unfinished,&rdquo; but we&rsquo;ll never know what the original finished work was to look like, or if its current state was as &ldquo;finished&rdquo; as Gainsborough and the Andrews wanted.</p>\n"
