"<h3>Beyond grace there is perfection</h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p>The supple and expressive quality of the dancing Shiva is one of the touchstones of South Asian, and indeed, world sculpture. When the French sculptor Auguste Rodin saw some photographs of the 11th century bronze <em>Shiva Nataraja</em> in the Madras Museum around 1915, he wrote that it seemed to him the &ldquo;perfect expression of rhythmic movement in the world.&rdquo; In an essay he wrote that was published in 1921 he wrote that the <em>Shiva Nataraja</em> has &ldquo;what many people cannot see&mdash;the unknown depths, the core of life. There is grace in elegance, but beyond grace there is perfection.&rdquo; The English philosopher Aldous Huxley said in an interview in 1961 that the Hindu image of god as a dancer is unlike anything he had seen in Western art. &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t have anything that approaches the symbolism of this work of art, which is both cosmic and psychological.&quot;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>The eloquent bronze statue of the <em>Shiva Nataraja</em>, despite the impact of its formal beauty on Rodin who knew little of its background, is incomplete without an understanding of its symbolism and religious significance. Bronzes of the Chola period such as <em>Shiva as Lord of the Dance (Nataraja)</em> arose out of a need to transmute the divine into a physical embodiment of beauty.</p>\n"
