"<p>I know, this table doesn&#39;t look nearly as readable as the old table that had all of information stuffed into every row. But, tables are often not designed to be readable to humans-- they&#39;re designed to be the best way to store data with the highest amount of maintainability and which is the least bug prone. In many cases, it may be best to split information into multiple related tables, so that there is less redundant data and less places to update.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>It&#39;s important to understand how to use SQL to deal with data that has been split up into multiple related tables, and bring the data back together across the tables when you need it. We do that using a concept called &quot;join&quot;s and that&#39;s what I&#39;ll show you next.</p>\n"

